</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Intestinal transplantation has evolved from its experimental origins in the mid–20th century to its status today as an established treatment option for patients with end-stage intestinal failure who cannot be sustained with total parenteral nutrition. The most common source of intestinal failure in both adults and children is short-bowel syndrome, but a host of other disease processes can lead to this common end-point. The development of intestinal transplantation has presented multiple hurdles for the transplant community, including technical challenges, immunologic pitfalls, and infectious complications. Despite these hurdles, the success rate has climbed over the past decades owing to achievements that include improved surgical techniques, new immunosuppressive regimens, and more effective strategies for posttransplant surveillance and management. Nearly 2800 intestinal transplants have been performed worldwide, and current patient and graft survival rates are now comparable to those of other types of solid organ transplantations. As their population continues to increase, it will be increasingly likely that intestinal-transplant patients will seek imaging at sites other than transplant centers. Therefore, it is important that diagnostic and interventional radiologists be familiar with the procedure, its common variations, and the spectrum of postoperative complications. In this article, the authors provide an overview of intestinal transplantation, including the indications, variations, expected postoperative anatomy, and range of potential complications.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170086">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170086">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig1.jpeg" height="1944" width="1784" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Illustration depicts IITx. Enteric anastomoses depicted include proximal side-to-side anastomosis between the native duodenum and donor jejunum and distal side-to-end anastomosis between the donor ileum and native sigmoid colon. Note the chimney ileostomy, which allows endoscopic access to perform biopsies to assess for rejection, and the percutaneous jejunostomy tube, which allows decompression and early enteral feeding. Vascular anastomoses depicted include arterial inflow of the native infrarenal aorta to the donor superior mesenteric artery (SMA) by an interposition graft and venous outflow of the donor superior mesenteric vein (SMV) draining into the native portal vein by an interposition graft. Insets show alternate options for vascular anastomoses. Arterial inflow options include donor SMA anastomosis to the native aorta directly to an iliac artery (top inset) or to the native abdominal aorta (bottom inset). Venous outflow options include donor SMV anastomosis to the inferior vena cava (IVC) by an interposition graft or directly to the left renal vein (top inset) or to the native SMV or native splenic vein (bottom inset). <i>Dark blue</i> <b>=</b> native veins, <i>dark red</i> <b>=</b> native arteries, <i>dark red-brown</i> <b>=</b> native organs<b>,</b> <i>light blue</i> <b>=</b> donor veins, <i>light brown</i> <b>=</b> donor organs, <i>light pink</i> <b>=</b> donor arteries. Keys are the same for Figures 1–<a href="#fig4">4</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig2.jpeg" height="2446" width="1565" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Illustration depicts L-ITx. Enteric anastomoses depicted include proximal side-to-side anastomosis between the native duodenum and donor jejunum and distal side-to-end anastomosis between the donor ileum and native sigmoid colon. Note the oversewn proximal donor duodenum, chimney ileostomy, and percutaneous jejunostomy tube. Vascular anastomoses depicted include arterial inflow of a Carrel patch (segment of donor aorta with its branches, including SMA and celiac axis) to the native infrarenal abdominal aorta and venous outflow of a segment of donor IVC, with confluence of hepatic veins, anastomosed in a piggyback fashion to the native IVC. The native splenic vein is diverted through an anastomosis to the native IVC (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig3.jpeg" height="2462" width="1591" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Illustration depicts full MVTx. Enteric anastomoses depicted include proximal end-to-end anastomosis between the native stomach and donor stomach and distal side-to-end anastomosis between the donor ileum and native sigmoid colon. Note the chimney ileostomy and percutaneous jejunostomy tube. Vascular anastomoses depicted include arterial inflow of the Carrel patch to the native infrarenal abdominal aorta and venous outflow of the segment of donor IVC, with confluence of hepatic veins, anastomosed in a piggyback fashion to the native IVC. Note that the donor SMV and donor portal vein (not shown) are not interrupted in this type of transplant and do not require anastomosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig4.jpeg" height="2332" width="1588" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Illustration depicts modified MVTx. Enteric anastomoses depicted include proximal end-to-end anastomosis between the native stomach and donor stomach; side-to-side native-to-donor duodenoduodenostomy to accommodate pancreatobiliary secretions; and distal side-to-side anastomosis between the donor ileum and oversewn native rectum. Note the chimney ileostomy. Vascular anastomoses in this surgery include arterial inflow of the Carrel patch to the native infrarenal abdominal aorta (not shown) and venous outflow of the donor SMV, directly anastomosed to the native portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig5.jpeg" height="1675" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Coronal oblique volume-rendered computed tomographic (CT) angiogram shows a donor SMA (arrow) anastomosed to the native infrarenal abdominal aorta in a 53-year-old woman who underwent IITx 4 months earlier for short-gut syndrome, which resulted from extensive enterectomy during treatment for mesenteric desmoid tumors.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig6.jpeg" height="1825" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiogram shows arterial supply arising from the right common iliac artery by a Carrel patch with a donor SMA (arrow), in a 30-year-old man with multiple gunshot wounds who underwent IITx.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig7.jpeg" height="1348" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 7</span>. Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiogram shows a donor aortic graft (black arrow) arising from the native infrarenal aorta in a patient who underwent MVTx. The donor SMA (white arrow) and celiac axis (white arrowhead) arise from the aortic graft. Note the native SMA stump (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig8.jpeg" height="1348" width="1750" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 8</span>. Intraoperative photograph shows the arterial anastomosis, an end-to-side anastomosis of the Carrel patch (black arrowhead) to the native infrarenal abdominal aorta (curved black arrow). Note the segment of donor aorta with its branches, including the SMA (straight black arrows) and celiac axis. Note also the venous anastomosis, an end-to-side anastomosis of the interposition graft (white arrowhead) to the native IVC (straight white arrow). The donor SMV (not shown) was later anastomosed in an end-to-end fashion to this interposition graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig9.jpeg" height="1331" width="1578" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 9</span>. Curved coronal venous phase maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT angiogram shows venous drainage after IITx for multiple gunshot wounds (same patient as in <a href="#fig6">Fig 6</a>). The donor SMV (arrow) connects to the native splenic vein (arrowhead) through an end-to-side anastomosis near the splenoportal confluence.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig10.jpeg" height="1331" width="1772" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 10</span>. Intraoperative photograph shows the venous anastomosis. The donor SMV is connected to a venous interposition graft (white arrow), which is connected to the native splenic vein (arrowhead). Note the partially visible arterial anastomosis, with the donor aorta (black arrow) connecting to the native aorta (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig11.jpeg" height="1703" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Short-gut syndrome as a complication of gastric bypass surgery in a 29-year-old woman. Small bowel follow-through fluoroscopic image, obtained as part of a preoperative evaluation before intestinal transplantation, shows the short length of residual small bowel (ending at the proximal jejunum) and the jejunocolonic anastomosis (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig12.jpeg" height="1371" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a 19-cm desmoid tumor (arrows) centered in the mesentery in a 23-year-old woman. CT was performed as part of a preoperative evaluation before intestinal transplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig13.jpeg" height="1701" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Selective angiogram of the SMA, performed as part of a preoperative evaluation, shows a paucity (arrow) of arterial branches in the ileal distribution, owing to prior small bowel resections in a 52-year-old woman with short-gut syndrome secondary to Crohn disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig14.jpeg" height="1239" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Preoperative evaluation for potential liver and small bowel transplantation in a 32-year-old woman with a history of necrotizing pancreatitis and chronic thrombosis of the SMV and splenic vein. Arterial portogram, obtained after injection of the splenic artery at delayed venous phase imaging, shows occlusion of the splenic vein, with opacification of the patent main portal vein (arrow) through large perigastric collaterals (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig15.jpeg" height="1694" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Mesenteric edema in a 49-year-old man with a history of multiple abdominal surgeries after a motor vehicle accident, which led to short-gut syndrome and IITx. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse mesenteric edema (arrow), an expected postoperative finding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig16.jpeg" height="1249" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Pneumatosis in a 36-year-old man who underwent IITx for short-gut syndrome, secondary to infantile volvulus. Axial nonenhanced CT image shows pneumatosis of the duodenum (arrow) and jejunum (arrowhead) 1 week after surveillance ileoscopy, an expected finding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig17.jpeg" height="1369" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Hepatic abscess after MVTx in a 40-year-old man with factor V Leiden mutation and Budd-Chiari syndrome, who presented with fever of unknown origin. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an ill-defined hypoattenuating multiloculated collection in the posterior right hepatic lobe (arrow), an hepatic abscess that was likely seeded through the portal venous system.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig18.jpeg" height="1145" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows patchy areas of airspace consolidation involving both lungs in a 33-year-old man with multifocal pneumonia who had previously undergone MVTx for extensive portosystemic thrombosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig19.jpeg" height="1056" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Chylous collection after IITx for short-gut syndrome secondary to mesenteric ischemia in a 26-year-old man. Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained 4 months after transplantation shows a large intraperitoneal collection with a nondependent fat-fluid level (arrow), typical of a chylous collection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig20a.jpeg" height="1308" width="1647" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Postoperative imaging after IITx for short-bowel syndrome related to multiple gunshot wounds in a 30-year-old man (same patient as in <a href="#fig6">Figs 6</a> and <a href="#fig9">9</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained in the early postoperative period shows diffuse mild dilatation of the small bowel secondary to ileus. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image, obtained 3 months later, shows resolved ileus with normal bowel caliber.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig20b.jpeg" height="1308" width="1703" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Postoperative imaging after IITx for short-bowel syndrome related to multiple gunshot wounds in a 30-year-old man (same patient as in <a href="#fig6">Figs 6</a> and <a href="#fig9">9</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained in the early postoperative period shows diffuse mild dilatation of the small bowel secondary to ileus. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image, obtained 3 months later, shows resolved ileus with normal bowel caliber.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig21a.jpeg" height="1181" width="1650" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Dilatation of the native duodenum in a 43-year-old woman with a history of chronic pseudo-obstruction who underwent IITx 9 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked dilatation of the native duodenum (arrow) owing to persistent pseudo-obstruction. A large volume of ascites is also depicted. <b>(b)</b> Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows the dilated native duodenum (arrow) with normal-caliber distal small bowel and colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig21b.jpeg" height="1931" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Dilatation of the native duodenum in a 43-year-old woman with a history of chronic pseudo-obstruction who underwent IITx 9 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked dilatation of the native duodenum (arrow) owing to persistent pseudo-obstruction. A large volume of ascites is also depicted. <b>(b)</b> Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows the dilated native duodenum (arrow) with normal-caliber distal small bowel and colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig22a.jpeg" height="1271" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Pseudoaneurysm in a 25-year-old man with Gardner syndrome who underwent MVTx 2 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large pseudoaneurysm (black arrow) involving the distal end of the Carrel patch/aortic graft. Note the severe mass effect from the pseudoaneurysm on the markedly attenuated left portal vein (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal catheter angiogram shows the large pseudoaneurysm (arrow) at the distal end of the Carrel patch/aortic graft. <b>(c)</b> Coronal arterial phase MIP image shows the aortic graft (arrow) arising from the native aorta and the large pseudoaneurysm (arrowhead) at the origin of the donor SMA from the aortic graft. <b>(d)</b> Coronal venous phase MIP image shows the aortic graft pseudoaneurysm (black arrow) compressing the main portal vein (arrowhead) and left portal vein (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig22b.jpeg" height="1524" width="1388" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Pseudoaneurysm in a 25-year-old man with Gardner syndrome who underwent MVTx 2 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large pseudoaneurysm (black arrow) involving the distal end of the Carrel patch/aortic graft. Note the severe mass effect from the pseudoaneurysm on the markedly attenuated left portal vein (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal catheter angiogram shows the large pseudoaneurysm (arrow) at the distal end of the Carrel patch/aortic graft. <b>(c)</b> Coronal arterial phase MIP image shows the aortic graft (arrow) arising from the native aorta and the large pseudoaneurysm (arrowhead) at the origin of the donor SMA from the aortic graft. <b>(d)</b> Coronal venous phase MIP image shows the aortic graft pseudoaneurysm (black arrow) compressing the main portal vein (arrowhead) and left portal vein (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig22c.jpeg" height="1524" width="972" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span>. Pseudoaneurysm in a 25-year-old man with Gardner syndrome who underwent MVTx 2 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large pseudoaneurysm (black arrow) involving the distal end of the Carrel patch/aortic graft. Note the severe mass effect from the pseudoaneurysm on the markedly attenuated left portal vein (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal catheter angiogram shows the large pseudoaneurysm (arrow) at the distal end of the Carrel patch/aortic graft. <b>(c)</b> Coronal arterial phase MIP image shows the aortic graft (arrow) arising from the native aorta and the large pseudoaneurysm (arrowhead) at the origin of the donor SMA from the aortic graft. <b>(d)</b> Coronal venous phase MIP image shows the aortic graft pseudoaneurysm (black arrow) compressing the main portal vein (arrowhead) and left portal vein (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig22d.jpeg" height="1524" width="1340" aria-labelledby="fig22d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22d</span>. Pseudoaneurysm in a 25-year-old man with Gardner syndrome who underwent MVTx 2 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large pseudoaneurysm (black arrow) involving the distal end of the Carrel patch/aortic graft. Note the severe mass effect from the pseudoaneurysm on the markedly attenuated left portal vein (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal catheter angiogram shows the large pseudoaneurysm (arrow) at the distal end of the Carrel patch/aortic graft. <b>(c)</b> Coronal arterial phase MIP image shows the aortic graft (arrow) arising from the native aorta and the large pseudoaneurysm (arrowhead) at the origin of the donor SMA from the aortic graft. <b>(d)</b> Coronal venous phase MIP image shows the aortic graft pseudoaneurysm (black arrow) compressing the main portal vein (arrowhead) and left portal vein (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig22d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig23a.jpeg" height="1216" width="1677" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. Subocclusive thrombus in a 26-year-old woman who underwent MVTx 6 years earlier for short-gut syndrome (due to presumed necrotizing enterocolitis as an infant) and impending liver failure. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram demonstrates a subocclusive thrombus in the distal portion of the aortic graft (white arrow) with a small residual patent lumen (arrowhead). Note that the native splenic vein is anastomosed to the native IVC (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiogram (posterior view) shows the thrombus as a luminal defect in the distal portion of the aortic graft (white arrow). Note the origin of the aortic graft from the infrarenal native aorta (arrowhead) and the native splenic vein anastomosed to the native IVC (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig23b.jpeg" height="1216" width="1272" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. Subocclusive thrombus in a 26-year-old woman who underwent MVTx 6 years earlier for short-gut syndrome (due to presumed necrotizing enterocolitis as an infant) and impending liver failure. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram demonstrates a subocclusive thrombus in the distal portion of the aortic graft (white arrow) with a small residual patent lumen (arrowhead). Note that the native splenic vein is anastomosed to the native IVC (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiogram (posterior view) shows the thrombus as a luminal defect in the distal portion of the aortic graft (white arrow). Note the origin of the aortic graft from the infrarenal native aorta (arrowhead) and the native splenic vein anastomosed to the native IVC (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig24a.jpeg" height="1088" width="1236" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. SMA thrombosis (arrow) in a 57-year-old woman with systemic lupus erythematosus and a history of SMA thrombosis, which led to IITx. <b>(a)</b> Selective arteriogram shows a thrombus in the proximal donor SMA, which was treated with overnight intra-arterial tissue plasminogen activator. <b>(b)</b> Repeat angiogram obtained the next day shows underlying anastomotic stenosis of the SMA. <b>(c)</b> Selective angiogram obtained after treatment with balloon angioplasty shows the relieved stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig24b.jpeg" height="1088" width="1236" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. SMA thrombosis (arrow) in a 57-year-old woman with systemic lupus erythematosus and a history of SMA thrombosis, which led to IITx. <b>(a)</b> Selective arteriogram shows a thrombus in the proximal donor SMA, which was treated with overnight intra-arterial tissue plasminogen activator. <b>(b)</b> Repeat angiogram obtained the next day shows underlying anastomotic stenosis of the SMA. <b>(c)</b> Selective angiogram obtained after treatment with balloon angioplasty shows the relieved stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig24c.jpeg" height="1088" width="1228" aria-labelledby="fig24c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24c</span>. SMA thrombosis (arrow) in a 57-year-old woman with systemic lupus erythematosus and a history of SMA thrombosis, which led to IITx. <b>(a)</b> Selective arteriogram shows a thrombus in the proximal donor SMA, which was treated with overnight intra-arterial tissue plasminogen activator. <b>(b)</b> Repeat angiogram obtained the next day shows underlying anastomotic stenosis of the SMA. <b>(c)</b> Selective angiogram obtained after treatment with balloon angioplasty shows the relieved stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig24c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig25.jpeg" height="1043" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span>. Donor SMV thrombus in a 53-year-old woman who underwent IITx 4 months earlier for short-gut syndrome, following extensive enterectomy related to mesenteric desmoid tumors (same patient as in <a href="#fig13">Fig 13</a>). Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a nearly occlusive donor SMV thrombus (white arrow). Note the adjacent patent donor SMA (black arrow). Pneumatosis of the distal ileum (not shown) and cecum (arrowheads) was caused by ileoscopy performed 1 day before this image was obtained. Ileoscopy repeated 1 day after CT revealed no evidence of ischemia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig26.jpeg" height="1350" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Recurrent thrombosis in a 22-year-old woman who presented with abdominal pain. The patient had undergone MVTx 6 months earlier for Budd-Chiari syndrome. Axial contrast-enhanced portal venous phase CT image shows recurrent thrombosis of the hepatic veins (white arrows) and donor IVC (black arrow) with hyperenhancement of the caudate lobe and central liver, consistent with recurrent Budd-Chiari syndrome. Note the prominent anterior and posterior abdominal wall collaterals (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig27.jpeg" height="1207" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Acute rejection in a 53-year-old man with a history of L-ITx for complications of Crohn disease. He presented 7 years later with diarrhea and weight loss. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in the arterial phase shows wall thickening and mild mucosal hyperenhancement of the distal ileum (arrow) and enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes (arrowhead). Ileoscopy (not shown) performed during the same admission showed findings of resolving acute rejection (mucosal ulceration and denuded mucosa with regenerating epithelium).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig28.jpeg" height="1339" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28</span>. Chronic rejection in a 53-year-old woman who underwent IITx for short-gut syndrome, secondary to inflammatory bowel disease and multiple bowel resections. Axial fat-saturated fast imaging employing steady-state acquisition (FIESTA) T2-weighted MR image obtained 19 years after IITx shows a long segment of distal bowel with wall thickening (arrow) but no surrounding mesenteric stranding or lymph node enlargement. Biopsy showed findings of chronic rejection. The patient also had a history of prior chronic rejection in the colon/rectum (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig29.jpeg" height="994" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig29" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span>. Periosteal reaction in a 40-year-old woman who underwent IITx for short-gut syndrome. Axial CT image obtained 5 years after IITx shows mature periosteal reaction along multiple ribs (arrows). Periosteal reaction also involved the bilateral humeral and femoral heads and the lumbar spine (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig29">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig30a.jpeg" height="1289" width="1227" aria-labelledby="fig30a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30a</span>. Intraluminal filling defects in a 24-year-old woman who underwent L-ITx for cryptogenic enteritis and presented with an obstructive pattern at liver function testing. <b>(a)</b> Coronal three-dimensional MRCP image during breath hold shows irregular contour of the extrahepatic common duct, with intraluminal filling defects (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Frontal ERCP image shows irregular filling defects in the extrahepatic common duct (arrow). Biliary casts were removed with the balloon sweep method.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig30a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig30b.jpeg" height="1289" width="1222" aria-labelledby="fig30b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30b</span>. Intraluminal filling defects in a 24-year-old woman who underwent L-ITx for cryptogenic enteritis and presented with an obstructive pattern at liver function testing. <b>(a)</b> Coronal three-dimensional MRCP image during breath hold shows irregular contour of the extrahepatic common duct, with intraluminal filling defects (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Frontal ERCP image shows irregular filling defects in the extrahepatic common duct (arrow). Biliary casts were removed with the balloon sweep method.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig30b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig31.jpeg" height="1224" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig31" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31</span>. Acute interstitial pancreatitis in a 64-year-old man with a history of L-ITx for short-gut syndrome due to mesenteric thrombosis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an edematous donor pancreas (arrow) with peripancreatic fat stranding and fluid (arrowhead). The native pancreas (not shown) was normal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig31">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig32a.jpeg" height="1598" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig32a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32a</span>. Chronic calcific pancreatitis in a 35-year-old man with a history of IITx for ultrashort-gut syndrome from multiple small bowel resections related to Crohn disease. Of note, the postoperative course was complicated by allograft enterectomy for chronic active cellular rejection and transmural ischemic necrosis of allograft bowel 1 year after transplantation. <b>(a)</b> Coronal two-dimensional thick-slab MRCP image obtained 2 years after transplantation shows irregular contour of the dilated native pancreatic duct (arrow) and an obstructing intraductal calculus, seen as an intraluminal filling defect (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image better shows the pancreatic parenchymal calcifications and intraductal calculus (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig32a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig32b.jpeg" height="1130" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig32b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32b</span>. Chronic calcific pancreatitis in a 35-year-old man with a history of IITx for ultrashort-gut syndrome from multiple small bowel resections related to Crohn disease. Of note, the postoperative course was complicated by allograft enterectomy for chronic active cellular rejection and transmural ischemic necrosis of allograft bowel 1 year after transplantation. <b>(a)</b> Coronal two-dimensional thick-slab MRCP image obtained 2 years after transplantation shows irregular contour of the dilated native pancreatic duct (arrow) and an obstructing intraductal calculus, seen as an intraluminal filling defect (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image better shows the pancreatic parenchymal calcifications and intraductal calculus (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig32b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig33" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig33.jpeg" height="1249" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig33" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33</span>. Chronic pancreatitis in a 45-year-old woman who underwent combined en-bloc intestinal and pancreatic transplantation 4 years earlier for short-gut syndrome, secondary to intestinal infarction from congenital malrotation and volvulus. Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows marked dilatation of the allograft main pancreatic duct (arrow), dilatation of ductal side branches, and surrounding parenchymal atrophy, compatible with changes of chronic pancreatitis. The patient had prior episodes of acute pancreatitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig33">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig34a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig34a.jpeg" height="1427" width="1703" aria-labelledby="fig34a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34a</span>. PTLD after modified MVTx for pseudo-obstruction and irreversible intestinal failure in an 18-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced positron emission tomography (PET)/CT fused image shows a large enhancing mesenteric mass (arrow) that avidly uptakes fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) and encases the aortic graft. <b>(b)</b> Coronal three-dimensional MIP PET image shows the FDG-avid mass (arrow). Biopsy confirmed PTLD. The patient had previously developed a hepatocellular carcinoma after transplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig34a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig34b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig34b.jpeg" height="1427" width="947" aria-labelledby="fig34b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34b</span>. PTLD after modified MVTx for pseudo-obstruction and irreversible intestinal failure in an 18-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced positron emission tomography (PET)/CT fused image shows a large enhancing mesenteric mass (arrow) that avidly uptakes fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) and encases the aortic graft. <b>(b)</b> Coronal three-dimensional MIP PET image shows the FDG-avid mass (arrow). Biopsy confirmed PTLD. The patient had previously developed a hepatocellular carcinoma after transplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig34b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig35a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig35a.jpeg" height="1295" width="1673" aria-labelledby="fig35a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 35a</span>. Hepatocellular carcinoma in an 18-year-old man who underwent modified MVTx 13 months earlier for pseudo-obstruction and irreversible intestinal failure (same patient as in <a href="#fig34a">Fig 34</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows a hypervascular mass (arrow) in segment VII of the native liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows the mass with washout (arrow) and capsular enhancement (arrowhead), which are characteristic findings of hepatocellular carcinoma. Biopsy confirmed this diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig35a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig35b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig35b.jpeg" height="1295" width="1677" aria-labelledby="fig35b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 35b</span>. Hepatocellular carcinoma in an 18-year-old man who underwent modified MVTx 13 months earlier for pseudo-obstruction and irreversible intestinal failure (same patient as in <a href="#fig34a">Fig 34</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows a hypervascular mass (arrow) in segment VII of the native liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows the mass with washout (arrow) and capsular enhancement (arrowhead), which are characteristic findings of hepatocellular carcinoma. Biopsy confirmed this diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig35b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig36" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig36.jpeg" height="1045" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig36" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 36</span>. Adenocarcinoma in a 50-year-old woman who underwent IITx for short-gut syndrome, secondary to acute vascular insufficiency of small bowel. Axial nonenhanced CT image shows multiple bilobar hypoattenuating hepatic lesions (arrows), which were new findings when compared with an immediate postoperative CT image obtained 9 months earlier (not shown). Biopsy showed moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of possible breast or urothelial origin, without a discernible primary tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig36">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig37" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig37.jpeg" height="1324" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig37" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 37</span>. Recurrent desmoid tumors in a 31-year-old woman who underwent MVTx owing to mesenteric desmoid tumors associated with Gardner syndrome. Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained 4 years after transplantation shows recurrent soft-tissue attenuation desmoid tumors in the anterior abdominal wall and posterior chest wall (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig37">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig38a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig38a.jpeg" height="1168" width="1244" aria-labelledby="fig38a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 38a</span>. Gastrointestinal adenoma in a 38-year-old woman who underwent IITx 3 years earlier for short-gut syndrome due to Gardner syndrome and intra-abdominal desmoid tumors. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows intrahepatic and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrowheads), with a periampullary mass in the distal common bile duct (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image of the right upper quadrant shows a hypoechoic solid mass (arrow) in the distal portion of the dilated common bile duct (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> ERCP image shows the mass as a filling defect (arrow) in the distal portion of the dilated common bile duct (arrowhead). Malignancy was suspected, but ERCP biopsy revealed a periampullary duodenal tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig38a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig38b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig38b.jpeg" height="1168" width="1906" aria-labelledby="fig38b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 38b</span>. Gastrointestinal adenoma in a 38-year-old woman who underwent IITx 3 years earlier for short-gut syndrome due to Gardner syndrome and intra-abdominal desmoid tumors. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows intrahepatic and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrowheads), with a periampullary mass in the distal common bile duct (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image of the right upper quadrant shows a hypoechoic solid mass (arrow) in the distal portion of the dilated common bile duct (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> ERCP image shows the mass as a filling defect (arrow) in the distal portion of the dilated common bile duct (arrowhead). Malignancy was suspected, but ERCP biopsy revealed a periampullary duodenal tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig38b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig38c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170086/asset/images/large/rg.2018170086.fig38c.jpeg" height="1307" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig38c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 38c</span>. Gastrointestinal adenoma in a 38-year-old woman who underwent IITx 3 years earlier for short-gut syndrome due to Gardner syndrome and intra-abdominal desmoid tumors. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows intrahepatic and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrowheads), with a periampullary mass in the distal common bile duct (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image of the right upper quadrant shows a hypoechoic solid mass (arrow) in the distal portion of the dilated common bile duct (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> ERCP image shows the mass as a filling defect (arrow) in the distal portion of the dilated common bile duct (arrowhead). Malignancy was suspected, but ERCP biopsy revealed a periampullary duodenal tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170086&amp;id=fig38c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Starzl TE, Rowe MI, Todo S, et al. Transplantation of multiple abdominal viscera. <em>JAMA</em> 1989;261(10):1449–1457.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.1989.03420100085029">Crossref</a></div>